commit.message:
Support Python 3.11 (#298)

* Support Python 3.11

* Upgrade setuptools in addition to pip

This is an attempt to fix the Python 3.11 on macos-latest

Besides, it is recommended pip and setuptools are up to date:
https://packaging.python.org/tutorials/installing-packages/#ensure-pip-setuptools-and-wheel-are-up-to-date

* Latest formal release of distutils/version.py

Python 3.11 does not ship with distutils. Python 3.10 series are the
last to ship distutils. Vendor from the current latest formal release,
Python 3.10.8:
https://github.com/python/cpython/blob/v3.10.8/Lib/distutils/version.py

Copy verbatim the Python LICENSE file:
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/python/cpython/v3.10.8/LICENSE

* Try `pip install` instead of `setup.py install`

commit.message:
Redundant wheel in pyproject.toml (#306)

The backend adds the wheel dependency automatically:
	The setuptools package implements the build_sdist command and
	the wheel package implements the build_wheel command; the latter
	is a dependency of the former exposed via PEP 517 hooks.

Listing it explicitly in the documentation was a historical mistake
and has been fixed since in pypa/setuptools@f7d30a9.

commit.message:
Remove more deprecated Python 2 stuff (#304)

* os.popen2 is deprecated → subprocess.run

See:
https://docs.python.org/3/library/subprocess.html#using-the-subprocess-module

* cPickle → pickle

In Python 2, cPickle is the accelerated version of pickle, and
a later addition to the standard library.

In Python 3 the accelerated version has been integrated and
there is simply no reason to use anything other than import pickle.

commit.message:
Apply some pyupgrade suggestions (#301)

* Apply some pyupgrade suggestions

The default mode for open() is 'r', a synonym of 'rt':
	https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#open

IOError is kept for compatibility with previous versions;
starting from Python 3.3, it is an alias of OSError:
	https://docs.python.org/3/library/exceptions.html#IOError

* Apply some refurb suggestions

* [FURB109]: Replace `in [x, y, z]` with `in (x, y, z)`
